awd_titl_txt: SHF:Small: Mega-Transfer: On the Value of Learning from 10,000+ Software Projects
awd_abstract_narration:
As more and more software and software-development artifacts have accumulated in large repositories, Software Engineering has become a Big Data Science.  Software analytics is a subfield of Software Engineering in which the software-project data is analyzed to gain actionable information that helps practitioners track and improve software-development practices. Research in software analytics seeks to develop better models, methods and tools to support, for example, software-defect prediction, using software production and programmer activity data. The first decade of software analytics has generated specific results about specific projects, but it remains difficult to generalize across many projects so that results on one project can be applied to other projects.  As in any big-data science, a central question is how much data, and of what quality, is needed to draw valid and useful conclusions that can generalize across multiple projects.  A typical research study in software analytics looks at no more than a few dozen projects, which limits the validity and usefulness of results in the field. The project will explore the sufficiency and limits of data for transfer learning across domains.  The ultimate goal is to scale software analytics, particularly transfer learning of nine extensively studied software-analytics tasks, to 10,000+ open-source projects and 1,500+ commercial projects. The result is software-quality prediction models, backed by large-scale quantitative studies, that can guide the development and maintenance of software, thus reducing the overall cost of creating and maintaining software.

The technical challenges of this work include scalability of the algorithms and the ability to transfer lessons learned between projects. To address these challenges this project will develop innovative transfer-learning methods based on fast linear-time clustering algorithms and fast stream-mining algorithms that use incremental hyper-parameter optimization and clustering.  The techniques will find similar projects in instance space (within each cluster) in order to find candidates for transfer. Further, where possible, this project will reduce the transfer cost by pre-studies that perform feature selection on the source and target data. Where it is found that software knowledge is highly localized, then this project will also develop and deploy optimization methods for large scale instance-based learning methods.

This award reflects NSF's statutory mission and has been deemed worthy of support through evaluation using the Foundation's intellectual merit and broader impacts review criteria.

por.por_cntn:
In the age of "big data" we ask:

  • Now to handle large data sets? Many SE research papers report resultf rom 1 to 10 projects. What can we report from 100 projects? from 1000 projects?
  • When is too much data? The more data we collect, the more likely it becomes that we collect additional spurious details. So how do we know when we can stop learning?

Two results from this work is that there is such a thing as too much data. For example, as part of this researcj, once we tried learning defect attributes from 700,000+ commits. Afer   a year of CPU (for the web data collection), the variances on the learned model were so large that we were unable to report a stable conclusion to our business users.

So large scale learning has to be very focused. In this research we showed that if we hieratchically cluster project data, then we can work formt eht leaft back to root of that cluster tree asking at each step "what is the best   model for sibling projects in the tree?". By pushing the best such model up the tree, we can collect a few models that "stand in for the rest".

 

For example, from 700 projects, we isolated 12 effort estimation models that stoff in for the rest. The exciting thing about this work is that this tree of clsuters can tell us if we ahve collected too much data

  • extra data is useful if it changes the "best models" fond by the above procedure
  • And useless otherwse.

Another exciting result from this work is that we found , from 1600 open source proejcts, we could predict the future state of open soruce projects 12 to 24 months into the future.Prior had work had trouble with this problem since most project last about 2-5 years and if we collect status information every month, that means we only get 24 to 60 rows of data per project. Fortuneately, with some hyperparameter optimziation, we found that effective models even though we had to learn from a very small space.For example, here is that method (called DECART) comapred to other learners, predicting various open source quality attribtes, 12 months into the future. Note that in this table, darker cells have lower error (i.e. are better results):

 

All these tools are depolyed in Docker containers and can be executed on your request at MolSSI (contact Dr. Paul Saxe).

So in sumamry, based on all the above, we recommend against learning from10,000 projects sicne very effective models can be learned from far less data.
